
Interview:
Linux shell commands are used in the terminal to perform file operations, navigation, and system tasks efficiently using simple text-based instructions.

Definitions:

Terminal: A command-line interface used to interact with the Linux system.

Directories usually appear in blue (or bold) while files appear in default color in terminal.

Basic Commands:
1)ls: Lists files and directories
ls -l: Shows detailed info including file type, permissions, owner, size, and timestamp.
E.g. 
bash
-rw-r--r-- 1 user user 123 file.txt
Meaning:

- → file
rw- → owner permissions
r-- → group
r-- → others

2)cd: Changes directory
cd .. : Moves one directory up

3)pwd: Shows current working directory

4)mkdir: Creates a new directory

5)Delete directory, files rm: Deletes a file, rm -r: Deletes a directory and its contents recursively , rmdir: Removes an empty directory

6)cat: Displays file content, zcat: Displays content of compressed .gz files
echo: Prints text to terminal 

echo "Hello World" > file.txt (Writes text to a file (overwrites if exists))
echo "Hello World" > newfile.txt (Creates new file and writes text)

7)touch: Creates an empty file

8)head: Shows first 10 lines of a file

9)tail: Shows last 10 lines of a file, tail -f: Continuously displays new lines added to a file (live logs)

10)less: Views file content page by page (scrollable), more: Views file content one screen at a time
clear: Clears the terminal screen (Utility command)

11) cp source destination

mv source destination
renaming also done using mv (e.g. mv devops/ linux_for_devops)

wc filename.txt
wc gives lines, words in number of files
E.g $ wc file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt
1 1 6 file1.txt (1 line, 1 word)
1 2 12 file2.txt (1 line, 2 words)
1 4 16 file3.txt (1 line 4 words)
12) vi editor in Unix and Linux OS - Is an editor that opens an editor on the terminal. 
After pressing I (insert mode), you can start typing. Once done, press Escape button, then :wq to save changes made in the vi or vim editor.

13)ln (soft link, hard link)
E.g. linux_for_devops/cloud$ echo "this is soft link" > devopsfile.txt
linux_for_devops/cloud$ cat devopsfile.txt 
this is soft link
linux_for_devops/cloud$ pwd 
/home/ubuntu/linux_for_devops/cloud
linux_for_devops/cloud$ cd
$ ln -s /home/ubuntu/linux_for_devops/cloud/devopsfile.txt softlink-file
$ls (softlink is created in /home/ubuntu)
softlink-file(in blue color) cloud demofile.txt linux_for_devops
$ ls -ltr gives detailed description of all files including the softlink created. 
Also if the original file is deleted, the softlink file will turn red in color.

Hardlink is created by the command: 
$ ln  /home/ubuntu/linux_for_devops/cloud/devopsfile.txt hardlink-file
$ rm home/ubuntu/linux_for_devops/cloud/devopsfile.txt
$ ls 
hardlink-file(remains white all the time) cloud demofile.txt linux_for_devops
Hardlink file will not turn red in color even if the source file is deleted.

14)cut
E.g. cut -b 1 myfile.txt (displays first byte in the file myfile.txt i.e. first letter)
cut -b 1-4 myfile.txt (displays first four bytes in the file myfile.txt i.e. first four letters)

tee - $ echo "hello" | tee hello.txt (displays and sends hello to hello.txt)
$ hello

sort - sorts the words in a file alphabetically

